'''Smoking cessation''' (colloquially '''quitting smoking''') is the process of discontinuing the practice of inhaling a [[smoking|smoked]] substance.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.cancer.org/docroot/ped/content/ped_10_13x_guide_for_quitting_smoking.asp| title=Guide to quitting smoking| publisher=[[American Cancer Society]]| date=2011-01-31| accessdate=2011-02-15}}</ref> This article focuses exclusively on cessation of [[tobacco smoking]]; however, the methods described may apply to cessation of smoking other substances that can be difficult to stop using due to the development of strong physical [[substance dependence]] or [[psychological dependence]] (addiction).

Smoking cessation can be achieved with or without assistance from healthcare professionals or the use of medications.<ref name=Chapman-MacKenzie>{{cite journal|title=The global research neglect of unassisted smoking cessation: causes and consequences|author=Chapman S, MacKenzie R|date=2010-02-09|journal=PLoS Medicine|publisher=Public Library of Science|url=http://www.plosmedicine.org/article/info%3Adoi%2F10.1371%2Fjournal.pmed.1000216|doi=10.1371/journal.pmed.1000216|pmid=20161722|volume=7|issue=2|pages=e1000216|pmc=2817714}}</ref> Methods that have been found to be effective include interventions directed at or via health care providers and health care systems; medications including [[nicotine replacement therapy]] (NRT) and [[varenicline]]; individual and group counselling; and Web-based or stand-alone and computer programs.  Although stopping smoking can cause short-term side effects such as reversible weight gain, smoking cessation services and activities are cost-effective because of the positive health benefits.

* In a growing number of countries, there are more ex-smokers than smokers.<ref name=Chapman-MacKenzie>{{cite journal|title=The Global Research Neglect of Unassisted Smoking Cessation: Causes and Consequences|author=Chapman, Simon and MacKenzie, Ross|date=February 9, 2010|journal=PLoS Medicine|publisher=Public Library of Science|url=http://www.plosmedicine.org/article/info%3Adoi%2F10.1371%2Fjournal.pmed.1000216|doi=10.1371/journal.pmed.1000216|pmid=20161722|volume=7|issue=2|pages=e1000216|pmc=2817714}}</ref>
* Early "failure" is a normal part of trying to stop, and more than one attempt at stopping smoking prior to longer-term success is common.<ref name=Chapman-MacKenzie />
* NRT, other prescribed pharmaceuticals, and professional counselling or support also help many smokers.<ref name=Chapman-MacKenzie />
* However, up to three-quarters of ex-smokers report having quit without assistance ("cold turkey" or cut down then quit), and cessation without professional support or medication may be the most common method used by ex-smokers.<ref name=Chapman-MacKenzie />

Tobacco contains the chemical [[nicotine]]. Smoking cigarettes can lead to [[nicotine addiction]].<ref name=Benowitz2010>{{Cite journal | author = Benowitz NL | last2 = Benowitz | first2 = Neal L. | title = Nicotine addiction | journal = N Engl J Med | volume = 362 | issue = 24 | pages = 2295–303 | year = 2010 | doi = 10.1056/NEJMra0809890 | pmid = 20554984 | pmc = 2928221}}</ref>{{rp|2300–2301}} The addiction begins when nicotine acts on [[nicotinic acetylcholine receptor]]s to release [[neurotransmitter]]s such as [[dopamine]], [[glutamate]], and [[gamma-aminobutyric acid]].<ref name=Benowitz2010/>{{rp|2296}}  Cessation of smoking leads to symptoms of nicotine withdrawal such as anxiety and irritability.<ref name=Benowitz2010/>{{rp|2298}}  Professional smoking cessation support methods generally endeavour to address both nicotine addiction and nicotine withdrawal symptoms.

Studies have shown that it takes between 6 to 12 weeks post quitting before the amount of nicotinic receptors in the brain return to the level of a non smoker.<ref>{{cite web|title=Abstinent Smokers' Nicotinic Receptors Take More Than a Month to Normalize|url=http://www.drugabuse.gov/news-events/nida-notes/2009/10/abstinent-smokers-nicotinic-receptors-take-more-than-month-to-normalize}}</ref>

== Methods ==
Major reviews of the scientific literature on smoking cessation include:
* [[Systematic review]]s of the Cochrane Tobacco Addiction Group of the [[Cochrane Collaboration]].<ref name=CochraneTAG>{{cite web |url= http://tobacco.cochrane.org/ |title=Welcome |author=Cochrane Tobacco Addiction Group |date=2010-03-02 |accessdate=2011-02-17}}</ref>  As of 2012, this independent, international, not-for-profit organization has published over 60 systematic reviews "on interventions to prevent and treat tobacco addiction"<ref name=CochraneTAG/> which will be referred to as "Cochrane reviews."
* ''Clinical Practice Guideline: Treating Tobacco Use and Dependence: 2008 Update'' of the [[United States Department of Health and Human Services]], which will be referred to as the "2008 Guideline."<ref name=USDHHS2008>{{cite book| title=Clinical practice guideline: treating tobacco use and dependence: 2008 update| author = Fiore MC, Jaén CR, Baker TB, et al|url=http://www.surgeongeneral.gov/tobacco/treating_tobacco_use08.pdf|publisher= U.S. Department of Health and Human Services, Public Health Service|location=Rockville, MD|year=2008| accessdate=2011-02-16}}</ref> The Guideline was originally published in 1996<ref>{{cite book |title=Smoking cessation. Clinical practice guideline no. 18 |author=Fiore MC, Bailey WC, Cohen SJ, et al |year=1996 |publisher=U.S. Department of Health and Human Services, Public Health Service, Agency for Health Care Policy and Research|location=Rockville, MD|series = AHCPR publication no. 96-0692}}</ref> and revised in 2000.<ref>{{cite book |title=Clinical practice guideline: treating tobacco use and dependence |author=Fiore MC, Bailey WC, Cohen SJ, et al |year=2000 |publisher= U.S. Department of Health and Human Services, Public Health Service|location=Rockville, MD | url = http://www.surgeongeneral.gov/tobacco/treating_tobacco_use.pdf | accessdate=2011-02-16}}</ref>  For the 2008 Guideline, experts screened over 8700 research articles published between 1975 and 2007.<ref name=USDHHS2008/>{{rp|13–14}} More than 300 studies were used in [[meta-analysis|meta-analyses]] of relevant treatments; an additional 600 reports were not included in meta-analyses, but helped formulate the recommendations.<ref name=USDHHS2008/>{{rp|22}} Limitations of the 2008 Guideline include its not evaluating studies of "cold turkey" methods ("unaided quit attempts") and its focus on studies that followed up subjects only to about 6 months after the "quit date" (even though almost one-third of former smokers who relapse before one year will do so 7–12 months after the "quit date").<ref name=USDHHS2008/>{{rp|19,23}}<ref>{{cite news |title= Conflict over officials’ stop-smoking advice|agency=Associated Press |url= http://www.msnbc.msn.com/id/24510715/38823217 |newspaper=msnbc.com |date= 2008-05-07|accessdate=2011-02-19}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal | author = Ferguson J, Bauld L, Chesterman J, Judge K | title = The English smoking treatment services: one-year outcomes | journal = Addiction | volume = 100 | issue =Suppl 2 | pages = 59–69 | year = 2005 | doi = 10.1111/j.1360-0443.2005.01028.x | pmid = 15755262 | url = http://whyquit.com/studies/2005_UK_NHS_1_Year_Ferguson.pdf}}</ref>

===Unassisted methods===
As it is common for ex-smokers to have made a number of attempts (often using different approaches on each occasion) to stop smoking before achieving long-term abstinence, identifying which approach or technique is eventually most successful is difficult; it has been estimated, for example, that "only about 4% to 7% of people are able to quit smoking on any given attempt without medicines or other help.".<ref name=ACS-success>{{cite web|title=Guide to quitting smoking. A word about quitting success rates|url=http://www.cancer.org/Healthy/StayAwayfromTobacco/GuidetoQuittingSmoking/guide-to-quitting-smoking-success-rates|publisher=American Cancer Society|date=2011-01-31|accessdate=2011-02-17}}</ref> However, in analysing a 1986 U.S. survey, Fiore ''et al''. (1990) found that 95% of former smokers who had been abstinent for 1–10 years had made an unassisted last quit attempt.<ref name=Fiore1990>{{cite journal |doi= 10.1001/jama.263.20.2760 |author= Fiore MC, Novotny TE, Pierce JP, Giovino GA, Hatziandreu EJ, Newcomb PA, Surawicz TS, Davis RM |year=1990 |title=Methods used to quit smoking in the United States. Do cessation programs help? |journal= JAMA |volume=263 |issue= 20 |pages=2760–5 | pmid=2271019 |url= http://jama.ama-assn.org/content/263/20/2760.full.pdf |accessdate=2011-02-19 }}</ref> The most frequent unassisted methods were "[[cold turkey]]" and "gradually decreased number" of cigarettes.<ref name=Fiore1990/> A 1995 meta-analysis estimated that the quit rate from unaided methods was 7.3% after an average of 10 months of follow-up.<ref>{{Cite journal | author = Baillie AJ, Mattick RP, Hall W | title = Quitting smoking: estimation by meta-analysis of the rate of unaided smoking cessation | journal = Aust J Public Health | volume = 19 | issue = 2 | pages = 129–31 | year = 1995 | doi = 10.1111/j.1753-6405.1995.tb00361.x | pmid = 7786936 }}</ref>

====Cold turkey====
"Cold turkey" is a colloquial term indicating abrupt withdrawal from an addictive drug, and in this context indicates sudden and complete cessation of all nicotine use. In three studies, it was the quitting method cited by 76%,<ref name=Lee2007>{{cite journal |doi= 10.2105/AJPH.2005.083527 |author= Lee CW, Kahende J |year=2007|title=Factors associated with successful smoking cessation in the United States, 2000 |journal= Am J Public Health|volume=97 |issue= 8|pages=1503–9 | pmid=17600268|url= http://ajph.aphapublications.org/cgi/content/full/97/8/1503 |accessdate=2011-02-19 |pmc= 1931453 }}</ref> 85%,<ref name=Fiore1990/> or 88%<ref>{{Cite journal | author = Doran CM, Valenti L, Robinson M, Britt H, Mattick RP | title = Smoking status of Australian general practice patients and their attempts to quit | journal = Addict Behav | volume = 31 | issue = 5 | pages = 758–66 | year = 2006 | doi = 10.1016/j.addbeh.2005.05.054 | pmid = 16137834 }}</ref> of long-term successful quitters. In a large British study of ex-smokers in the 1980s, before the advent of pharmacotherapy, 53% of the ex-smokers said that it was "not at all difficult" to stop, 27% said it was "fairly difficult", and the remaining 20% found it very difficult.<ref name=Chapman-MacKenzie />  Cold turkey methods have been advanced by J. Wayne McFarland and Elman J. Folkenburg;<ref>{{cite news|title=New book details history of LLU bringing ‘Health to the People’|url=http://www.llu.edu/news/today/today_story.page?id=1468|date=2008-03-31|publisher=Loma Linda University|accessdate=2011-02-15}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|author=McFarland JW, Folkenberg EJ|title=How to stop smoking in five days|year=1964|publisher=Prentice-Hall|location=Englewood Cliffs, NJ}}</ref> [[Joel Spitzer]] and John R. Polito;<ref>{{cite web|title=WhyQuit|url=http://www.whyquit.com/|publisher=WhyQuit|accessdate=2011-02-20}}</ref> and [[Allen Carr]].<ref name=Carr2004>{{Cite book | author = Carr A | title = The easy way to stop smoking | year =2004 | publisher = Sterling | location =New York | isbn = 1-4027-7163-0}}</ref>

===Healthcare provider and system interventions===
Interventions delivered via healthcare providers and healthcare systems have been shown to improve smoking cessation among people who visit those providers.
* A clinic screening system (e.g., computer prompts) to identify whether or not a person smokes doubled abstinence rates, from 3.1% to 6.4%.<ref name=USDHHS2008/>{{rp|78–79}} Similarly, the Task Force on Community Preventive Services determined that provider reminders alone or with provider education are effective in promoting smoking cessation.<ref name=Hopkins2001>{{Cite journal | doi = 10.1016/S0749-3797(00)00297-X | author = Hopkins DP, Briss PA, Ricard CJ, Husten CG, Carande-Kulis VG, Fielding JE, Alao MO, McKenna JW, Sharp DJ, Harris JR, Woollery TA, Harris KW; Task Force on Community Preventive Services | title = Reviews of evidence regarding interventions to reduce tobacco use and exposure to environmental tobacco smoke | journal = Am J Prev Med | volume = 20 | issue = 2 Suppl | pages = 16–66 | year = 2001 | pmid = 11173215 | url = http://www.thecommunityguide.org/tobacco/tobac-AJPM-evrev.pdf}}</ref>{{rp|33–38}}
* A 2008 Guideline meta-analysis estimated that physician advice to quit smoking led to a quit rate of 10.2%, as opposed to a quit rate of 7.9% among patients who did not receive physician advice to quit smoking.<ref name=USDHHS2008/>{{rp|82–83}} A Cochrane review found that even brief advice from physicians had "a small effect on cessation rates."<ref>{{Cite journal | author = Stead LF, Bergson G, Lancaster T | editor1-last = Stead | editor1-first = Lindsay F | title = Physician advice for smoking cessation | journal = Cochrane Database Syst Rev | issue = 2 | pages = CD000165 | year = 2008 | doi = 10.1002/14651858.CD000165.pub3 | pmid = 18425860 | url = http://www2.cochrane.org/reviews/en/ab000165.html}}</ref> However, one study from Ireland involving [[Vignette (psychology)|vignettes]] found that physicians' probability of giving smoking cessation advice declines with the patient's age,<ref>{{Cite journal | doi = 10.1093/ageing/29.3.264 | author = Maguire CP, Ryan J, Kelly A, O'Neill D, Coakley D, Walsh JB | title = Do patient age and medical condition influence medical advice to stop smoking? | journal = Age Ageing | volume = 29 | issue = 3 | pages = 264–6 | year = 2000 | url = http://ageing.oxfordjournals.org/content/29/3/264.long | pmid = 10855911 }}</ref> and another study from the U.S. found that only 81% of smokers age 50 or greater received advice on quitting from their physicians in the preceding year.<ref name="Ossip-Klein-2000">{{Cite journal | author = Ossip-Klein DJ, McIntosh S, Utman C, Burton K, Spada J, Guido J | title = Smokers ages 50+: who gets physician advice to quit? | journal = Prev Med | volume = 31 | issue = 4 | pages = 364–9 | year = 2000 | doi = 10.1006/pmed.2000.0721 | pmid = 11006061 | url = http://cvhpinstitute.org/hls396/pdf/Smokers%2050+.pdf}}</ref>
* For one-to-one or person-to-person counselling sessions, the duration of each session, the total amount of contact time, and the number of sessions all correlated with the effectiveness of smoking cessation. For example, "Higher intensity" interventions (>10 minutes) produced a quit rate of 22.1% as opposed to 10.9% for "no contact"; over 300 minutes of contact time produced a quit rate of 25.5% as opposed to 11.0% for "no minutes"; and more than 8 sessions produced a quit rate of 24.7% as opposed to 12.4% for 0–1 sessions.<ref name=USDHHS2008/>{{rp|83–86}}
* Both physicians and non-physicians increased abstinence rates compared with self-help or no clinicians.<ref name=USDHHS2008/>{{rp|87–88}} For example, a Cochrane review of 31 studies found that nursing interventions increased the likelihood of quitting by 28%.<ref>{{Cite journal | author = Rice VH, Stead LF | editor1-last = Rice | editor1-first = Virginia Hill | title = Nursing interventions for smoking cessation | journal = Cochrane Database Syst Rev | issue = 1 | pages = CD001188 | year = 2008 | doi = 10.1002/14651858.CD001188.pub3 | pmid = 18253987 | url = http://www2.cochrane.org/reviews/en/ab001188.html}}</ref>
* Dental professionals also provide a key component in increasing tobacco abstinance rates in the community through counseling patients on the effects of tobacco on oral health in conjunction with an oral exam.<ref>Carr AB, Ebbert J. interventions for tobacco cessation in the dental setting. Cochrane Database of Systematic Reviews 2012, Issue 6. Art. No.: CD005084. DOI: 10.1002/14651858.CD005084.pub3</ref>
* According to the 2008 Guideline, based on two studies the training of clinicians in smoking cessation methods may increase abstinence rates<ref name=USDHHS2008/>{{rp|130}}; however, a Cochrane review found "a measurable effect" that such training decreased smoking in patients.<ref>{{cite journal |author=Carson KV, Verbiest ME, Crone MR, ''et al.'' |title=Training health professionals in smoking cessation |journal=Cochrane Database Syst Rev |volume=5 |issue= |pages=CD000214 |year=2012 |pmid=22592671 |doi=10.1002/14651858.CD000214.pub2}}</ref>
* Reducing or eliminating the costs of cessation therapies for smokers increased quit rates in three meta-analyses.<ref name=USDHHS2008/>{{rp|139–140}}<ref name=Hopkins2001/>{{rp|38–40}}<ref>{{Cite journal | author = Reda AA, Kaper J, Fikrelter H, Severens JL, van Schayck CP | editor1-last = Van Schayck | editor1-first = Constant Paul | title = Healthcare financing systems for increasing the use of tobacco dependence treatment | journal = Cochrane Database Syst Rev | issue = 2 | pages = CD004305 | year = 2009 | doi = 10.1002/14651858.CD004305.pub3 | pmid = 19370599 | url = http://www2.cochrane.org/reviews/en/ab004305.html }}</ref>
* In one systematic review and meta-analysis, multi-component interventions increased quit rates in [[primary care]] settings.<ref>{{Cite journal | author = Papadakis S, McDonald P, Mullen KA, Reid R, Skulsky K, Pipe A| title = Strategies to increase the delivery of smoking cessation treatments in primary care settings: a systematic review and meta-analysis | journal = Prev Med | volume = 51 | issue = 3–4 | pages = 199–213 | year = 2010  | doi = 10.1016/j.ypmed.2010.06.007 | pmid = 20600264 }}</ref> "Multi-component" interventions were defined as those that combined two or more of the following strategies known as the "5 A's"<ref name=USDHHS2008/>{{rp|38–43}}:
** Ask — Systematically identify all tobacco users at every visit
** Advise — Strongly urge all tobacco users to quit[[File:Breath CO Monitor.jpg|thumb|upright=.6|Breath CO monitor displaying carbon monoxide concentration of an exhaled breath sample (in ppm) with its corresponding percent concentration of carboxyhemoglobin.]]
** Assess — Determine willingness to make a quit attempt
** Assist — Aid the patient in quitting (provide counselling-style support and medication)
** Arrange — Ensure follow-up contact

===Biochemical feedback===
Various methods exist which allow a smoker to see the impact of their tobacco use, and the immediate effects of quitting.  Using biochemical feedback methods can allow tobacco-users to be identified and assessed, and the use of monitoring throughout an effort to quit can increase motivation to quit.<ref name="Bittoun">Bittoun R.  (2008). Carbon monoxide meter: The essential clinical tool- the ‘stethoscope"-of smoking cessation.   Journal of Smoking Cessation, 3(2); 69-70.</ref><ref>Jamrozik K, Vessey M, Fowler G, Nicholas W, Parker G, and van Vunakis H.  (1984).  Controlled trial of three different anti-smoking interventions in general practice.  British Medical Journal, 288; 1499-1503.</ref>

* Breath carbon monoxide (CO) monitoring:  Because [[carbon monoxide]] is a significant component of cigarette smoke, a [[breath carbon monoxide monitor]] can be used to detect recent cigarette use.  Carbon monoxide concentration in breath has been shown to be directly correlated with the CO concentration in blood, known as percent [[carboxyhemoglobin]].  The value of demonstrating blood CO concentration to a smoker through a non-invasive breath sample is that it links the smoking habit with the physiological harm associated with smoking.<ref>Irving JM, Clark EC, Crombie IK, and Smith WC. (1988). Evaluation of a portable measure of expired-air carbon monoxide. Preventive Medicine, 17; 109-115.</ref> Within hours of quitting, CO concentrations show a noticeable decrease, and this can be encouraging for someone working to quit.  Breath CO monitoring has been utilized in smoking cessation as a tool to provide patients with biomarker feedback, similar to the way in which other diagnostic tools such as the stethoscope, the blood pressure cuff, and the cholesterol test have been used by treatment professionals in medicine.<ref name="Bittoun" />
* Cotinine:  A [[metabolite]] of nicotine, cotinine is present in smokers.  Like carbon monoxide, a cotinine test can serve as a reliable biomarker to determine smoking status.<ref>Florescu A, Ferrence R, Einarson T, Selby P, Soldin O, Koren G (February 2009). "Methods for quantification of exposure to cigarette smoking and environmental tobacco smoke: focus on developmental toxicology". Therapeutic Drug Monitoring 31 (1): 14–30. {{doi|10.1097/FTD.0b013e3181957a3b}}. PMID 19125149.</ref> Cotinine levels can be tested through urine, saliva, blood, or hair samples, with one of the main concerns of cotinine testing being the invasiveness of typical sampling methods.

While both measures offer high sensitivity and specificity, they differ in usage method and cost. As an example, breath CO monitoring is non-invasive, while cotinine testing relies on a bodily fluid.  These two methods can be used either alone or together, for example, in a situation where abstinence verification needs additional confirmation.<ref>5.	McClure JB.  (2002). Are biomarkers useful treatment aids for promoting health behavior change? American Journal of Preventive Medicine, 22 (3); 200-207.</ref>

===Single medications===
[[Image:Nicoderm.JPG||thumb|A 21mg dose [[Nicoderm]] CQ patch applied to the left arm.]]
The [[American Cancer Society]] estimates that "between about 25% and 33% of smokers who use medicines can stay smoke-free for over 6 months."<ref name=ACS-success/> Single medications include:
* [[Nicotine replacement therapy]] (NRT): Five medications approved by the U.S. [[Food and Drug Administration]] (FDA) deliver nicotine in a form that does not involve the risks of smoking. NTRs are meant to be used for a short period of time and should be tapered down to a low dose before stopping. The five NRT medications, which in a Cochrane review increased the chances of stopping smoking by 50 to 70% compared to placebo or to no treatment,<ref name=CD000146>{{cite journal|author=Stead LF, Perera R, Bullen C, Mant D, Lancaster T|editor1-last=Stead|editor1-first=Lindsay F|title=Nicotine replacement therapy for smoking cessation|url=http://www2.cochrane.org/reviews/en/ab000146.html|journal = Cochrane Database Syst Rev | pages = CD000146|year=2008|issue=1 |doi=10.1002/14651858.CD000146.pub3|accessdate=2011-02-16|pmid = 18253970 }}</ref> are:
*# transdermal [[nicotine patch]]es deliver doses of the addictive chemical [[nicotine]], thus reducing the unpleasant effects of nicotine withdrawal. These patches can give smaller and smaller doses of nicotine, slowly reducing dependence upon nicotine and thus tobacco. A Cochrane review found further increased chance of success in a combination of the nicotine patch and a faster acting form.<ref name=CD000146 /> Also, this method becomes most effective when combined with other medication and psychological support.<ref>{{cite news|author=Noble HB|work=New York Times|title=New from the smoking wars: success|url=http://www.nytimes.com/1999/03/02/science/new-from-the-smoking-wars-success.html|date=1999-03-02|accessdate=2011-02-19}}</ref>
*# [[nicotine gum|gum]]
*# [[Nicotine lozenge|lozenges]]
*# sprays
*# [[inhaler]]s.
:A study found that 93 percent of over-the-counter NRT users relapse and return to smoking within six months.<ref>{{cite news|author=Millstone K|title=Nixing the patch: Smokers quit cold turkey|url=http://jscms.jrn.columbia.edu/cns/2007-02-13/millstone-coldturkeyquitters.html|date=2007-02-13 |publisher=Columbia.edu News Service|accessdate=2011-02-21}}</ref>
* [[Antidepressant]]: [[Bupropion]] is FDA-approved and is marketed under the brand name Zyban. Bupropion is contraindicated in [[epilepsy]], seizure disorder; anorexia/bulimia (eating disorders), patients' use of antidepressant drugs (MAO inhibitors) within 14 days, patients undergoing abrupt discontinuation of ethanol or sedatives (including benzodiazepines such as Valium).<ref>{{Cite book | author = Lacy CF et al| title = Drug information handbook | edition= 12th | year = 2004 | publisher = Lexi-Comp | location =Hudson, OH | isbn = 1-59195-083-X }}</ref><ref name=Hughes2007>{{Cite journal | author = Hughes JR, Stead LF, Lancaster T | editor1-last = Hughes | editor1-first = John R | title = Antidepressants for smoking cessation | journal = Cochrane Database Syst Rev | issue = 1 | pages = CD000031 | year = 2007 | doi = 10.1002/14651858.CD000031.pub3 | pmid = 17253443 | url = http://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/10.1002/14651858.CD000031/pdf }}</ref>
* [[Nicotinic receptor]] [[partial agonist]]s:
** [[Cytisine]] (Tabex) is a plant extract that has been in use since the 1960s in former Soviet-bloc countries.<ref>{{Cite journal  | author = Etter JF, Lukas RJ, Benowitz NL, West R, Dresler CM | title = Cytisine for smoking cessation: a research agenda | journal = Drug Alcohol Depend | volume = 92  | issue = 1–3 | pages = 3–8 | year = 2008 | doi = 10.1016/j.drugalcdep.2007.06.017 | pmid = 17825502 }}</ref> It was the first medication approved as an aid to smoking cessation, and has very few side effects in small doses.<ref>{{cite book|author=Herrick C, Herrick C, Mitchell M|title=100 questions & answers about how to quit smoking|location=Sudbury, MA |publisher=Jones and Bartlett|year=2009|isbn=0-7637-5741-1|page=112}}</ref><ref name=WestShiffman2007>{{cite book|author=West R, Shiffman S|title=Fast facts: smoking cessation|publisher=Health Press Ltd|location=Abingdon, England|year=2007|edition=2nd|isbn=978-1-903734-98-8}}</ref>{{rp|70}}
** [[Varenicline]] tartrate is a prescription drug marketed by [[Pfizer]] as Chantix in the U.S. (under FDA approval) and as Champix outside the U.S.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.pfizer.com/files/annualreport/2008/annual/review2008.pdf |title=Doing things differently. Annual review 2008 |author=Pfizer |year=2009|accessdate=2011-02-22}}</ref> Synthesized as an improvement upon cytisine,<ref>{{cite news |title=Design of an antismoking pill. The makers of varenicline got their inspiration from two natural products |author=Yarnell A |url=http://pubs.acs.org/cen/news/83/i23/8323antismoking.html |newspaper=Chemical & Engineering News |date=2005-05-31 |accessdate=2011-02-22}}</ref> varenicline decreases the urge to smoke and reduces withdrawal symptoms.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://webprod.hc-sc.gc.ca/dpd-bdpp/item-iteme.do?pm-mp=00010641 |title=Product monograph. <sup>Pr</sup>Champix (varenicline tartrate tablets) |author=Pfizer Canada Inc|date=2010-05-28|accessdate=2011-02-22}}</ref> Two systematic reviews and meta-analyses supported by unrestricted funding from Pfizer, one in 2006<ref>{{Cite journal | author = Wu P, Wilson K, Dimoulas P, Mills EJ | title = Effectiveness of smoking cessation therapies: a  | journal = BMC Public Health | volume = 6 | page = 300 | year = 2006 | doi = 10.1186/1471-2458-6-300 | pmc = 1764891 | pmid = 17156479 | url = http://www.biomedcentral.com/1471-2458/6/300/}}</ref> and one in 2009,<ref>{{Cite journal | author = Mills EJ, Wu P, Spurden D, Ebbert JO, Wilson K | title = Efficacy of pharmacotherapies for short-term smoking abstinance: a systematic review and meta-analysis | journal = Harm Reduct J | volume = 6 | page = 25 | year = 2009 | doi = 10.1186/1477-7517-6-25 | pmc = 2760513 | pmid = 19761618 | url = http://www.harmreductionjournal.com/content/6/1/25 | issue=1}}</ref> found varenicline more effective than NRT or bupropion. A table in the 2008 Guideline indicates that 2&nbsp;mg/day of varenicline leads to the highest abstinence rate (33.2%) of any single therapy, while 1&nbsp;mg/day leads to an abstinence rate of 25.4%.<ref name=USDHHS2008/>{{rp|109}} A 2011 Cochrane review of 15 studies (13 of which had been sponsored by Pfizer) found that varenicline was significantly superior to bupropion at one year but that varenicline and nicotine patches produced the same level of abstinence at 24 weeks.<ref name=Cahill2011>{{Cite journal | author = Cahill K, Stead LF, Lancaster T | editor1-last = Cahill | editor1-first = Kate | title = Nicotine receptor partial agonists for smoking cessation | journal = Cochrane Database Syst Rev | volume = 2 | issue = 2 | pages = CD006103 | year = 2011 | doi = 10.1002/14651858.CD006103.pub5 | pmid = 21328282 | url = http://www2.cochrane.org/reviews/en/ab006103.html|accessdate=2011-02-25}}</ref> A 2011 review of double-blind studies found that varenicline has increased risk of [[Heart|serious adverse cardiovascular event]]s compared with placebo.<ref>{{cite journal|author=Singh S, Loke Y, Spangler J, and Furberg C|title=Risk of serious adverse cardiovascular events associated with varenicline: a systematic review and meta-analysis|url=http://www.cmaj.ca/content/early/2011/07/04/cmaj.110218.full.pdf+html|format=PDF|journal=Canadian Medical Association Journal (CMAJ)|doi=10.1503/cmaj.110218 |date=July 4, 2011|accessdate=July 4, 2011|pmid=21727225|pmc=3168618|volume=183|issue=12|pages=1359–66}}</ref> Varenicline may cause neuropsychiatric side effects; for example, in 2008 the U.K. [[Medicines and Healthcare products Regulatory Agency]] issued a warning about possible suicidal thoughts and suicidal behavior associated with varenicline.<ref>{{cite journal |author=Medicines and Healthcare products Regulatory Agency |date=2008 July |title=Drug safety advice. Varenicline: suicidal thoughts and behaviour |journal= Drug Safety Update|volume=1 |issue=12 |pages=2–3 |url=http://www.mhra.gov.uk/home/groups/pl-p/documents/publication/con020567.pdf |accessdate=2011-02-21 }}</ref>

*[[Moclobemide]] has been tested in heavy dependent smokers against placebo based on the theory that tobacco smoking could be a form of self medicating of [[major depression]],<ref name="Berlin-1995">{{Cite journal  | last1 = Berlin | first1 = I. | last2 = Saïd | first2 = S. | last3 = Spreux-Varoquaux | first3 = O. | last4 = Launay | first4 = JM. | last5 = Olivares | first5 = R. | last6 = Millet | first6 = V. | last7 = Lecrubier | first7 = Y. | last8 = Puech | first8 = AJ. | title = A reversible monoamine oxidase A inhibitor (moclobemide) facilitates smoking cessation and abstinence in heavy, dependent smokers. | journal = Clin Pharmacol Ther | volume = 58 | issue = 4 | pages = 444–52 | month = Oct | year = 1995 | doi = 10.1016/0009-9236(95)90058-6 | PMID = 7586937 }}</ref> and moclobemide could therefore help increase abstinence rates due to moclobemide mimicking the [[MAO-A]] inhibiting effects of [[tobacco smoke]]. Moclobemide was administered for 3 months and then stopped; at 6 months follow-up it was found those who had taken moclobemide for 3 months had a much higher successful quit rate than those in the placebo group. However, at 12 month follow-up the difference between the placebo group and the moclobemide group was no longer significant.<ref name="Hughes-2007">{{Cite journal  | last1 = Hughes | first1 = JR. | last2 = Stead | first2 = LF. | last3 = Lancaster | first3 = T. | title = Antidepressants for smoking cessation. | journal = Cochrane Database Syst Rev | issue = 1 | pages = CD000031 | month =  | year = 2007 | doi = 10.1002/14651858.CD000031.pub3 | PMID = 17253443 | url = http://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/10.1002/14651858.CD000031.pub3/full }}</ref>

Two other medications have been used in trials for smoking cessation, although they are not approved by the FDA for this purpose. They may be used under careful physician supervision if the first line medications are contraindicated for the patient.
# [[Clonidine]] may reduce withdrawal symptoms and "approximately doubles abstinence rates when compared to a placebo," but its side effects include dry mouth and sedation, and abruptly stopping the drug can cause high blood pressure and other side effects.<ref name=USDHHS2008/>{{rp|55,116–117}}<ref>{{Cite journal | author = Gourlay SG, Stead LF, Benowitz NL | editor1-last = Stead | editor1-first = Lindsay F | title = Clonidine for smoking cessation | journal = Cochrane Database Syst Rev | issue = 3 | pages = CD000058 | year = 2004 | doi = 10.1002/14651858.CD000058.pub2 | pmid = 15266422 | url = http://www2.cochrane.org/reviews/en/ab000058.html }}</ref>
# [[Nortriptyline]], another antidepressant, has similar success rates to bupropion but has side effects including dry mouth and sedation.<ref name=USDHHS2008/>{{rp|56,117–118}}<ref name=Hughes2007/>

===Combinations of medications===
The 2008 US Guideline specifies that three combinations of medications are effective<ref name=USDHHS2008/>{{rp|118–120}}:
* Long-term nicotine patch and ''ad libitum'' NRT gum or spray
* Nicotine patch and nicotine inhaler
* Nicotine patch and bupropion (the only combination that the US FDA has approved for smoking cessation)

===Cut down to quit===
Gradual reduction involves slowly reducing one's daily intake of nicotine. This can theoretically be accomplished through repeated changes to cigarettes with lower levels of nicotine, by gradually reducing the number of cigarettes smoked each day, or by smoking only a fraction of a cigarette on each occasion. A 2009 systematic review by researchers at the [[University of Birmingham]] found that gradual nicotine replacement therapy could be effective in smoking cessation.<ref>{{cite news|author=Phend C|title=Gradual cutback with nicotine replacement boosts quit rates |url=http://www.medpagetoday.com/PrimaryCare/Smoking/13590|date=2009-04-03|publisher=MedPage Today|accessdate=2011-02-20}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal | author = Moore D, Aveyard P, Connock M, Wang D, Fry-Smith A, Barton P | title = Effectiveness and safety of nicotine replacement therapy assisted reduction to stop smoking: systematic review and meta-analysis | journal = BMJ | volume = 338 | pages = b1024 | year = 2009 | doi = 10.1136/bmj.b1024 | pmc = 2664870 | pmid = 19342408 | url = http://www.bmj.com/content/338/bmj.b1024.full}}</ref> A 2010 Cochrane review found that abrupt cessation and gradual reduction with [[nicotine replacement therapy|pre-quit NRT]] produced similar quit rates whether or not pharmacotherapy or psychological support was used.
<ref>{{cite news|author=Joseph J|title=
Cut down to quit approach no better|url=http://www.pharmacynews.com.au/article/Cut-down-to-quit-approach-no-better/514634.aspx|date=March 30, 2010|work=Pharmacy News|publisher=Reed Business Information}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|author=Lindson N, Aveyard P, Hughes JR|editor1-last=Lindson|editor1-first=Nicola|title=Reduction versus abrupt cessation in smokers who want to quit|url=http://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/10.1002/14651858.CD008033/pdf|year=2010|issue=3|doi=10.1002/14651858.CD008033.pub2|accessdate=May 20, 2010|pmid=20238361|volume=3|pages=CD008033|journal=Cochrane Database Syst Rev}}</ref> 
According to a more recent 2012 [[Cochrane Collaboration|Cochrane]] [[systematic review]] analysis of 10 studies and 3670 patients, overall [[relative risk reduction]] between smokers who attempted to quit with abrupt cessation or with gradual reduction techniques was 0.06. This analysis demonstrated that there was no significant difference in quit rates between smokers who quit by gradual reduction or abrupt cessation as measured by abstinence from smoking of at least six months from the quit day, suggesting that patients who want to quit can choose between these two methods.<ref>{{cite journal|author= Lindson-Hawley N, Aveyard P, Hughes JR |title= Reduction versus abrupt cessation in smokers who want to quit|url= http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/23152252|year=2012|issue=11| DOI= 10.1002/14651858.CD008033.pub3|pmid=23152252|journal= Cochrane Database of Systematic Reviews }}</ref>

===Community interventions===
A Cochrane review found evidence that community interventions using "multiple channels to provide reinforcement, support and norms for not smoking" had an effect on smoking cessation outcomes among adults.<ref>{{Cite journal | author = Secker-Walker RH, Gnich W, Platt S, Lancaster T | editor1-last = Stead | editor1-first = Lindsay F | title = Community interventions for reducing smoking among adults | journal = Cochrane Database Syst Rev | issue = 3 | pages = CD001745 | year = 2002 | doi = 10.1002/14651858.CD001745 | pmid = 12137631 | url = http://www2.cochrane.org/reviews/en/ab001745.html}}</ref> Specific methods used in the community to encourage smoking cessation among adults include:
* Policies making workplaces<ref name=Lee2007/> and public places smoke-free. It is estimated that "comprehensive clean indoor laws" can increase smoking cessation rates by 12%–38%.<ref name=Lemmens2008>{{Cite journal | author = Lemmens V, Oenema A, Knut IK, Brug J| title = Effectiveness of smoking cessation interventions among adults: a systematic review of reviews | journal = Eur J Cancer Prev | volume = 17 | issue = 6 | pages = 535–44 | year = 2008 | doi = 10.1097/CEJ.0b013e3282f75e48 | pmid = 18941375 | url = http://www.cmtabaquismo.com.ar/documentos/Lemmens%20et%20al%20EJCP%202008%20Cochrane%20intervenciones.pdf}}</ref>
* Voluntary rules making homes smoke-free, which are thought to promote smoking cessation.<ref name=Lee2007/><ref name=CDC2007>{{cite journal | url = http://www.cdc.gov/mmwr/preview/mmwrhtml/mm5620a3.htm | pmid = 17522588 | volume=56 | issue=20 | title=State-specific prevalence of smoke-free home rules--United States, 1992-2003 | year=2007 | month=May | pages=501–4 | author=Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC) | journal=MMWR Morb. Mortal. Wkly. Rep.}}</ref>
* Initiatives to educate the public regarding the health effects of [[second-hand smoke]].
* Increasing the price of tobacco products, for example by taxation. The US Task Force on Community Preventive Services found "strong scientific evidence" that this is effective in increasing tobacco use cessation.<ref name=Hopkins2001/>{{rp|28–30}} It is estimated that an increase in price of 10% will increase smoking cessation rates by 3–5%.<ref name=Lemmens2008/>
* [[Mass media]] campaigns. The US Task Force on Community Preventive Services declared that "strong scientific evidence" existed for these when "combined with other interventions"<ref name=Hopkins2001/>{{rp|30–32}}, but a Cochrane review concluded that it was "difficult to establish their independent role and value".<ref>{{Cite journal | author = Bala M, Strzeszynski L, Cahill K | editor1-last = Bala | editor1-first = Malgorzata| title = Mass media interventions for smoking cessation in adults | journal = Cochrane Database Syst Rev | issue = 1 | pages = CD004704 | year = 2008 | doi = 10.1002/14651858.CD004704.pub2 | pmid = 18254058 | url = http://www2.cochrane.org/reviews/en/ab004704.html }}</ref>

===Competitions and incentives===
One 2008 Cochrane review concluded that "incentives and competitions have not been shown to enhance long-term cessation rates."<ref>{{Cite journal | author = Cahill K, Perera R | editor1-last = Cahill | editor1-first = Kate | title = Competitions and incentives for smoking cessation | journal = Cochrane Database Syst Rev | issue = 3 | pages = CD004307 | year = 2008 | doi = 10.1002/14651858.CD004307.pub3 | pmid = 18646105 | url = http://www2.cochrane.org/reviews/en/ab004307.html}}</ref> However, a trial published in 2009 found that financial incentives for smoking cessation led to significantly higher rates of smoking cessation 15–18 months after enrollment.<ref>{{Cite journal | author = Volpp KG, Troxel AB, Pauly MV, Glick HA, Puig A, Asch DA, Galvin R, Zhu J, Wan F, DeGuzman J, Corbett E, Weiner J, Audrain-McGovern J | title = A randomized, controlled trial of financial incentives for smoking cessation | journal = N Engl J Med | volume = 360 | issue = 7 | pages = 699–709 | year = 2009 | doi = 10.1056/NEJMsa0806819 | pmid = 19213683 | url = http://www.nejm.org/doi/full/10.1056/NEJMsa0806819}}</ref> Furthermore, a different 2008 Cochrane review found that one type of competition, "Quit and Win," did increase quit rates among participants.<ref>{{Cite journal | author = Cahill K, Perera R | editor1-last = Cahill | editor1-first = Kate | title = Quit and Win contests for smoking cessation | journal = Cochrane Database Syst Rev | issue = 4 | pages = CD004986 | year = 2008 | doi = 10.1002/14651858.CD004986.pub3 | pmid = 18843674 | url = http://www2.cochrane.org/reviews/en/ab004986.html}}</ref>

===Psychosocial approaches===
* [[Great American Smokeout]] is an annual event that invites smokers to quit for one day, hoping they will be able to extend this forever.
* The World Health Organization's [[World No Tobacco Day]] is held on May 31 each year.
* Smoking-cessation support  is often offered over the internet, over the telephone [[quitline]]s<ref name=Zhu2002>{{Cite journal | author = [[Zhu S-H|Zhu SH]], Anderson CM, Tedeschi GJ, Rosbrook B, Johnson CE, Byrd M, Gutiérrez-Terrell E | title = Evidence of real-world effectiveness of a telephone quitline for smokers | journal = N Engl J Med | volume = 347 | issue = 14 | pages = 1087–93 | year = 2002 | doi = 10.1056/NEJMsa020660 | pmid = 12362011 | url = http://www.nejm.org/doi/full/10.1056/NEJMsa020660}}</ref><ref name=Helgason2004>{{Cite journal | doi = 10.1093/eurpub/14.3.306 | author = [[Asgeir Helgason|Helgason AR]], Tomson T, Lund KE, Galanti R, Ahnve S, Gilljam H | title = Factors related to abstinence in a telephone helpline for smoking cessation | journal = Eur J Public Health | volume = 14 | issue = 3 | pages = 306–10 | year = 2004 | url = http://eurpub.oxfordjournals.org/content/14/3/306.full.pdf | pmid = 15369039 }}</ref> (e.g., the US toll-free number 1-800-QUIT-NOW), or in person. Three meta-analyses have concluded that telephone cessation support is effective when compared with minimal or no counselling or self-help, and that telephone cessation support with medication is more effective than medication alone.<ref name=USDHHS2008/>{{rp|91–92}}<ref name=Hopkins2001/>{{rp|40–42}}<ref>{{Cite journal | author = Stead LF, Perera R, Lancaster T | editor1-last = Stead | editor1-first = Lindsay F | title = Telephone counselling for smoking cessation | journal = Cochrane Database Syst Rev | volume = 3 | issue = 3 | pages = CD002850 | year = 2006 | doi = 10.1002/14651858.CD002850.pub2 | pmid = 16855992 | url = http://www2.cochrane.org/reviews/en/ab002850.html }}</ref>
* Group or individual psychological support can help people who want to quit. This form of counselling can be effective alone; combining it with medication is more effective, and the number of sessions of support with medication correlates with effectiveness.<ref name=USDHHS2008/>{{rp|89–90,101–103}}<ref>{{Cite journal | author = Stead LF, Lancaster T | editor1-last = Stead | editor1-first = Lindsay F | title = Group behaviour therapy programmes for smoking cessation | journal = Cochrane Database Syst Rev | issue = 2 | pages = CD001007 | year = 2005 | doi = 10.1002/14651858.CD001007.pub2 | pmid = 15846610 | url = http://www2.cochrane.org/reviews/en/ab001007.html }}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal | author = Lancaster T, Stead LF | editor1-last = Lancaster | editor1-first = Tim | title = Individual behavioural counselling for smoking cessation | journal = Cochrane Database Syst Rev | issue = 2 | pages = CD001292 | year = 2005 | doi = 10.1002/14651858.CD001292.pub2 | pmid = 15846616 | url = http://www2.cochrane.org/reviews/en/ab001292.html }}</ref> The counselling styles that have been effective in smoking cessation activities include [[motivational interviewing]]<ref>{{Cite journal | author = Lai DT, Cahill K, Qin Y, Tang JL | editor1-last = Lai | editor1-first = Douglas TC | title = Motivational interviewing for smoking cessation | journal = Cochrane Database Syst Rev | issue = 1 | pages = CD006936 | year = 2010 | doi = 10.1002/14651858.CD006936.pub2 | pmid = 20091612 | url = http://www2.cochrane.org/reviews/en/ab006936.html }}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal | author = Hettema JE, Hendricks PS| title = Motivational interviewing for smoking cessation: a meta-analytic review | journal = J Consult Clin Psychol | volume = 78 | issue = 6 | pages = 868–84 | year = 2010 | doi = 10.1037/a0021498 | pmid = 21114344 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal | author = Heckman CJ, Egleston BL, Hofmann MT| title = Efficacy of motivational interviewing for smoking cessation: a systematic review and meta-analysis | journal = Tob Control | volume = 19 | issue = 5 | pages = 410–6 | year = 2010 | doi = 10.1136/tc.2009.033175 | pmc = 2947553 | pmid = 20675688 }}</ref> and [[cognitive behavioural therapy]].<ref>{{Cite book | author = Perkins KA, Conklin CA, Levine MD | title = Cognitive-behavioral therapy for smoking cessation: a practical guidebook to the most effective treatment | year = 2008 | publisher = Routledge | location = New York | isbn = 978-0-415-95463-1 }}</ref>
*The Freedom From Smoking® group clinic includes eight sessions and features a step-by-step plan for quitting smoking. Each session is designed to help smokers gain control over their behavior. The clinic format encourages participants to work on the process and problems of quitting both individually and as part of a group<ref>http://www.lung.org/stop-smoking/how-to-quit/freedom-from-smoking/</ref>
* Multiple formats of psychosocial interventions increase quit rates: 10.8% for no intervention, 15.1% for one format, 18.5% for 2 formats, and 23.2% for three or four formats.<ref name=USDHHS2008/>{{rp|91}}
* The [[Transtheoretical Model]] including "stages of change" has been used in tailoring smoking cessation methods to individuals.<ref>{{cite journal |doi= 10.1037/0022-006X.56.4.520 |author= Prochaska JO, Velicer WF, DiClemente CC, Fava J |year=1988 |title= Measuring processes of change: applications to the cessation of smoking |journal= J Consult Clin Psychol |volume= 56 |issue= 4 |pages= 520–8 |pmid= 3198809}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.1037/0022-006X.59.2.295 |author=DiClemente CC, Prochaska JO, Fairhurst SK, Velicer WF, Velasquez MM, Rossi JS |year= 1991|title= The process of smoking cessation: an analysis of precontemplation, contemplation, and preparation stages of change|journal= J Consult Clin Psychol |volume= 59 |issue=2 |pages= 295–304 |pmid= 2030191 |url= http://www.uri.edu/research/cprc/Publications/PDFs/ByTitle/The%20Process%20of%20smoking%20cessation%20an%20analysis%20of%20precomtemplation.pdf |accessdate=2011-02-15}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |doi= 10.1037/0033-2909.111.1.23 |author= Velicer WF, Prochaska JO, Rossi JS, Snow MG |year= 1992 |title= Assessing outcome in smoking cessation studies |journal= Psychol Bull |volume= 111 |issue= 1|pages= 23–41 |pmid= 1539088 |accessdate=2011-02-15}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |doi= 10.1037/0278-6133.12.5.399 |author= Prochaska JO, DiClemente CC, Velicer WF, Rossi JS |year= 1993 |title= Standardized, individualized, interactive, and personalized self-help programs for smoking cessation |journal= Health Psychol |volume= 12 |issue= 5 |pages= 399–405 |pmid= 8223364 |url= http://www.uri.edu/research/cprc/Publications/PDFs/ByTitle/Standardized%20individualized%20interactive%20and%20Personalized.pdf |accessdate=2011-02-15}}</ref> However, a 2010 Cochrane review concluded that "stage-based self-help interventions (expert systems and/or tailored materials) and individual counselling were neither more nor less effective than their non-stage-based equivalents."<ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.1002/14651858.CD004492.pub4 |author=Cahill K, Lancaster T, Green N |year=2010 |editor1-last=Cahill |editor1-first=Kate |title=Stage-based interventions for smoking cessation |journal=Cochrane Database Syst Rev |issue= 11|pages=CD004492 |pmid=21069681 |url=http://www2.cochrane.org/reviews/en/ab004492.html |accessdate=2011-02-15}}</ref>

===Self-help===
A 2005 Cochrane review found that self-help materials may produce only a small increase in quit rates.<ref>{{Cite journal | author = Lancaster T, Stead LF | editor1-last = Lancaster | editor1-first = Tim | title = Self-help interventions for smoking cessation | journal = Cochrane Database Syst Rev | issue = 3 | pages = CD001118 | year = 2005 | doi = 10.1002/14651858.CD001118.pub2 | pmid = 16034855 | url = http://www2.cochrane.org/reviews/en/ab001118.html}}</ref> In the 2008 Guideline, "the effect of self-help was weak," and the number of types of self-help did not produce higher abstinence rates.<ref name=USDHHS2008/>{{rp|89–91}}  Nevertheless, self-help modalities for smoking cessation include:
* In-person self-help groups such as [[Nicotine Anonymous]]<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.nicotine-anonymous.org/ | title=Nicotine Anonymous (official website)| publisher = Nicotine Anonymous World Services|location = Dallas, TX|accessdate=2011-02-21}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal | author = Glasser I | title = Nicotine Anonymous may benefit nicotine-dependent individuals | journal = Am J Public Health | volume = 100 | issue = 2 | page = 196 |  year = 2010 | doi = 10.2105/AJPH.2009.181545 | pmid = 20019295 }}</ref> or electronic self-help groups such as Stomp It Out.<ref>{{cite web
| url=http://www.experienceproject.com/mk/smokefree/index.php | title=Stomp It Out| publisher = Experience Project|location = San Francisco, CA|accessdate=2011-02-21}}</ref>
* [[Newsgroups]]: The [[Usenet]] group [[alt.* hierarchy|alt]].support.stop-smoking has been used by people quitting smoking as a place to go to for support from others.<ref>{{cite news |title=Breaking the habit - these tips can keep your good intentions from going up in smoke |author=Uhler D |date=1995-11-15|newspaper=San Antonio Express-News}}</ref> It is accessible through [[Google Groups]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://groups.google.com/group/alt.support.stop-smoking/topics?hl=en |author = Google Groups|title=alt.support.stop-smoking |accessdate=2011-02-21}}</ref> and is now also available as an online forum, at http://www.as3-web.org/discuss .
* Interactive web-based and stand-alone computer programs and online communities which assist participants in quitting, such as [http://www.becomeanex.org/ EX] and [http://forums.quitnet.com/community/talk/ QuitNet].  For example, "quit meters" keep track of statistics such as how long a person has remained abstinent.<ref>{{cite news |title= Computer is an ally in quit-smoking fight. Study shows web- and computer-based programs help smokers quit|author=Hendrick B |url= http://www.webmd.com/smoking-cessation/news/20090526/computer-is-an-ally-in-quit-smoking-fight|newspaper=WebMD Health News|date= 2009-05-26|accessdate=2011-02-21}}</ref> In the 2008 US Guideline, there was no meta-analysis of computerised interventions, but they were described as "highly promising."<ref name=USDHHS2008/>{{rp|93–94}} A meta-analysis published in 2009,<ref>{{Cite journal | author = Myung SK, McDonnell DD, Kazinets G, Seo HG, Moskowitz JM | title = Effects of Web- and computer-based smoking cessation programs: meta-analysis of randomized controlled trials | journal = Arch Intern Med | volume = 169 | issue = 10 | pages = 929–37 | year = 2009 | doi = 10.1001/archinternmed.2009.109 | pmid = 19468084 | url = http://archinte.ama-assn.org/cgi/content/full/169/10/929}}</ref> a Cochrane review published in 2010,<ref>{{Cite journal | author = Civljak M, Sheikh A, Stead LF, Car J | editor1-last = Car | editor1-first = Josip | title = Internet-based interventions for smoking cessation | journal = Cochrane Database Syst Rev | issue = 9 | pages = CD007078 | year = 2010 | doi = 10.1002/14651858.CD007078.pub3 | pmid = 20824856 | url = http://www2.cochrane.org/reviews/en/ab007078.html}}</ref> and a 2011 systematic review<ref>{{Cite journal | author = Hutton HE, Wilson LM, Apelberg BJ, Avila Tang E, Odelola O, Bass EB, Chander G | title = A systematic review of randomized controlled trials: web-based interventions for smoking cessation among adolescents, college students, and adults | journal = Nicotine Tob Res | pages = [Epub ahead of print] | month = Feb | year = 2011 | doi = 10.1093/ntr/ntq252 | pmid = 21350042 | volume = 13 | issue = 4 }}</ref> found the evidence base for such interventions weak.
* [[Mobile phone]]-based interventions: A 2009 Cochrane review stated that "more evidence is needed" to determine the effectiveness of such interventions.<ref>{{Cite journal | author = Whittaker R, Borland R, Bullen C, Lin RB, McRobbie H, Rodgers A | editor1-last = Whittaker | editor1-first = Robyn | title = Mobile phone-based interventions for smoking cessation | journal = Cochrane Database Syst Rev | issue = 4 | pages = CD006611 | year = 2009 | doi = 10.1002/14651858.CD006611.pub2 | pmid = 19821377 | url = http://www2.cochrane.org/reviews/en/ab006611.html}}</ref> As of 2009, a randomised trial of mobile phone-based smoking cessation support was underway in the U.K.<ref>{{Cite journal | author = Free C, Whittaker R, Knight R, Abramsky T, Rodgers A, Roberts IG | title = Txt2stop: a pilot randomised controlled trial of mobile phone-based smoking cessation support | journal = Tob Control | volume = 18 | issue = 2 | pages = 88–91 | year = 2009 | doi = 10.1136/tc.2008.026146 | pmid = 19318534 }}</ref>
* [[Self-help|Self-help books]] such as [[Allen Carr]]'s ''Easy Way to Stop Smoking''.<ref name=Carr2004/>
* [[Spirituality]]: In one survey of adult smokers, 88% reported a history of spiritual practice or belief, and of those more than three-quarters were of the opinion that using spiritual resources may help them quit smoking.<ref>{{Cite journal | author = Gonzales D, Redtomahawk D, Pizacani B, Bjornson WG, Spradley J, Allen E, Lees P| title = Support for spirituality in smoking cessation: results of pilot survey | journal = Nicotine Tob Res | volume = 9 | issue = 2 | pages = 299–303 | year = 2007 | doi = 10.1080/14622200601078582 | pmid = 17365761 }}</ref>

===Substitutes for cigarettes===
* [[Electronic cigarette]]: Shaped like a cigarette to emulate the tactile experience of smoking, electronic cigarettes contain a rechargeable battery and a heating element which vaporises liquid nicotine and other flavorings from an insertable cartridge.  Proponents of electronic cigarettes often market them as a smoking cessation device. Many claim that electronic cigarettes deliver the experience of smoking without the adverse health effects usually associated with tobacco smoke, or at least greatly reduce those risks.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.absolutelyecigs.com/blog/e-cigarette-excellent-subsitute-tobacco-cigarettes/|title=E-Cigarette – An Excellent Subsitute to Tobacco Cigarettes|date=25 January 2012|publisher=AbsolutelyeCigs.com|accessdate=9 May 2012}}</ref>  However, in September 2008, the [[World Health Organization]] issued a release proclaiming that it does not consider the electronic cigarette to be a legitimate smoking cessation aid, stating that "no rigorous, peer-reviewed studies have been conducted showing that the electronic cigarette is a safe and effective [[nicotine replacement therapy]]."<ref name="WHO">{{cite web |url=http://www.who.int/mediacentre/news/releases/2008/pr34/en/index.html|title=Marketers of electronic cigarettes should halt unproved therapy claims|accessdate=2011-02-21|date=2008-09-19|publisher=World Health Organization}}</ref>
* The US National Institute of Health recommends chewing cinnamon sticks when trying to quit the use of tobacco. In addition to raw cinnamon sticks, cinnamon-flavoured toothpicks are used to help curb the urge for tobacco.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nlm.nih.gov/medlineplus/ency/article/001992.htm |title=Smoking - tips on how to quit |publisher=Nlm.nih.gov |date=2012-07-27 |accessdate=2012-08-05}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.candycrate.com/candycrate-in-the-news.html |title=Cinnamon Curbs the Urge and More |publisher=Candycrate.com |date= |accessdate=2012-08-05}}</ref>
* Plastic cigarette substitute:  In one 2006 study, giving people a free "Better Quit" hollow tube resembling a cigarette did not improve quit rates.<ref>{{Cite journal | author = Bauer JE, Carlin-Menter SM, Celestino PB, Hyland A, Cummings KM | title = Giving away free nicotine medications and a cigarette substitute (Better Quit) to promote calls to a quitline | journal = J Public Health Manag Pract | volume = 12 | issue = 1 | pages = 60–7 | year = 2006  | pmid = 16340517 | url = http://journals.lww.com/jphmp/Fulltext/2006/01000/Giving_Away_Free_Nicotine_Medications_and_a.12.aspx}}</ref>

===Alternative approaches===
* [[Acupuncture]]: A Cochrane review concluded that acupuncture "do[es] not appear to help smokers who are trying to quit",<ref>{{cite journal|author=White AR, Rampes H, Liu JP, Stead LF, Campbell J|editor1-last=White|editor1-first=Adrian R|title=Acupuncture and related interventions for smoking cessation|url=http://www2.cochrane.org/reviews/en/ab000009.html|year=2011|issue=1|doi=10.1002/14651858.CD000009.pub3|accessdate=2011-02-14|pmid=21249644|pages=CD000009|journal=Cochrane Database Syst Rev}}</ref> a meta-analysis from the 2008 Guideline showed no difference between acupuncture and placebo<ref name=USDHHS2008/>{{rp|99–100}}, and the 2008 Guideline found no scientific studies supporting laser therapy based on acupuncture principles but without the needles.<ref name=USDHHS2008/>{{rp|99}}.
* [[Aromatherapy]]: A 2006 book reviewing the scientific literature on aromatherapy<ref>{{Cite book | author = Lis-Balchin M | title = Aromatherapy science: a guide for healthcare professionals | year = 2006 | publisher = Pharmaceutical Press | location = London | isbn = 0-85369-578-4 | page =101 }}</ref> identified only one study on smoking cessation and aromatherapy; the study found that "inhalation of vapor from [[black pepper]] extract reduces smoking withdrawal symptoms".<ref>{{Cite journal | author= Rose JE, Behm FM | title = Inhalation of vapor from black pepper extract reduces smoking withdrawal symptoms | journal = Drug Alcohol Depend | volume = 34 | issue= 3 | pages = 225–9 | year = 1994 | doi = 10.1016/0376-8716(94)90160-0 | pmid = 8033760 }}</ref>
* [[Hypnosis]]:  Hypnosis often involves the hypnotherapist suggesting to the patient the unpleasant outcomes of smoking.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.webmd.com/smoking-cessation/hypnosis-for-quitting-smoking|title=Hypnosis for Quitting Smoking|publisher=WebMD|accessdate=19 May 2012}}</ref>  Clinical trials studying hypnosis and [[hypnotherapy]] as a method for smoking cessation have been inconclusive<ref name=USDHHS2008/>{{rp|100}};<ref>{{Cite journal | author = Barnes J, Dong CY, McRobbie H, Walker N, Mehta M, Stead LF | editor1-last = Barnes | editor1-first = Jo | title = Hypnotherapy for smoking cessation | journal = Cochrane Database Syst Rev | issue = 10 | pages = CD001008 | year = 2010 | doi = 10.1002/14651858.CD001008.pub2 | pmid = 20927723 | url = http://www2.cochrane.org/reviews/en/ab001008.html}}</ref> however, a randomized trial published in 2008 found that hypnosis and nicotine patches "compares favorably" with standard behavioral counseling and nicotine patches in 12-month quit rates.<ref>{{Cite journal | author = Carmody TP, Duncan C, Simon JA, Solkowitz S, Huggins J, Lee S, Delucchi K | title = Hypnosis for smoking cessation: a randomized trial | journal = Nicotine Tob Res | volume = 10 | issue = 5 | pages = 811–8 | year = 2008 | doi = 10.1080/14622200802023833 | pmid = 18569754 }}</ref>
*[[Herbs]]:  Many herbs have been studied as a method for smoking cessation, including [[lobelia]] and [[St John's wort]].<ref name=wart>
{{Cite journal | author = Mayo Clinic title = St. John's Wort for Tobacco Cessation url = http://clinicaltrials.gov/ct2/show/NCT00405912}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Mayo|first=Clinic|title=St. John's Wort for Tobacco Cessation|url=http://clinicaltrials.gov/ct2/show/NCT00405912|publisher=US National Institute of Health|accessdate=29 November 2006}}</ref> The results are inconclusive, but St. Johns Wort shows few adverse events. Lobelia has been used to treat respiratory diseases like asthma and bronchitis, and has been used for smoking cessation because of chemical similarities to tobacco; lobelia is now listed in the FDA's Poisonous Plant Database.<ref>{{Cite journal | author = FDA title = FDA Poisonous Plant Database url = http://www.accessdata.fda.gov/scripts/Plantox/Detail.CFM?ID=21006}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=FDA|title=FDA Poisonous Plant Database|url=http://www.accessdata.fda.gov/scripts/Plantox/Detail.CFM?ID=21006|publisher=U.S. Food and Drug Administration|accessdate=1 January 2008}}</ref> Lobelia can still be found in many products sold for smoking cessation and should be used with caution.

==Smoking cessation in special populations==

===Children and adolescents===
Methods used with children and adolescents include:
* Motivational enhancement<ref name=Grimshaw2006>{{Cite journal | author = Grimshaw GM, Stanton A | editor1-last = Grimshaw | editor1-first = Gill | title = Tobacco cessation interventions for young people | journal = Cochrane Database Syst Rev | issue = 4 | pages = CD003289 | year = 2006 | doi = 10.1002/14651858.CD003289.pub4 | pmid = 17054164 | url = http://www2.cochrane.org/reviews/en/ab003289.html}}</ref>
* Psychological support<ref name=Grimshaw2006/>
* Youth anti-tobacco activities, such as sport involvement
* School-based curricula, such as life-skills training
* Access reduction to tobacco
* Anti-tobacco media
* Family communication
A Cochrane review, mainly of studies combining motivational enhancement and psychological support, concluded that "complex approaches" for smoking cessation among young people show promise.<ref name=Grimshaw2006/> The 2008 US Guideline recommends counselling-style support for adolescent smokers on the basis of a meta-analysis of seven studies.<ref name=USDHHS2008/>{{rp|159–161}}  Neither the Cochrane review nor the 2008 Guideline recommends medications for adolescents who smoke.

===Pregnant women===
[[Smoking and pregnancy|Smoking during pregnancy]] can cause adverse health effects in both the woman and the fetus.  The 2008 US Guideline determined that "person-to-person psychosocial interventions" (typically including "intensive counseling") increased abstinence rates in pregnant women who smoke to 13.3%, compared with 7.6% in usual care.<ref name=USDHHS2008/>{{rp|165–167}} Mothers who smoke during pregnancy have a greater tendency towards premature births. Their babies are often underdeveloped,  have smaller organs, and weigh much less compared with the normal baby. In addition, these babies have worse immune systems, making them more susceptible to many diseases in early childhood, such as middle ear inflammations and asthmatic bronchitis which can bring about a lot of agony and suffering. As well, there is a high chance that they will become smokers themselves when grown up.<ref>{{cite web|last=Philip|first=Owen|title=Pregnancy and Smoking|url=http://www.netdoctor.co.uk/health_advice/facts/pregnantsmoking.htm|publisher=Net Doctor|accessdate=9 April 2012}}</ref>

===Workers===
A 2008 Cochrane review of smoking cessation activities in work-places concluded that "interventions directed towards individual smokers increase the likelihood of quitting smoking."<ref>{{Cite journal | author = Cahill K, Moher M, Lancaster T | editor1-last = Cahill | editor1-first = Kate | title = Workplace interventions for smoking cessation | journal = Cochrane Database Syst Rev | issue = 4 | pages = CD003440 | year = 2008 | doi = 10.1002/14651858.CD003440.pub3 | pmid = 18843645 | url = http://www2.cochrane.org/reviews/en/ab003440.html}}</ref> A 2010 systematic review determined that worksite incentives and competitions needed to be combined with additional interventions to produce significant increases in smoking cessation rates.<ref name=Leeks2010>{{Cite journal | author = Leeks KD, Hopkins DP, Soler RE, Aten A, Chattopadhyay SK; Task Force on Community Preventive Services | title = Worksite-based incentives and competitions to reduce tobacco use. A systematic review | journal = Am J Prev Med | volume = 38 | issue = 2 Suppl | pages = S263–74 | year = 2010 | doi = 10.1016/j.amepre.2009.10.034 | pmid = 20117611 | url = http://www.thecommunityguide.org/tobacco/worksite/Worksite2010Incentives_Leek.pdf}}</ref>

===Hospitalised smokers===
[[File:Smoking cessation-West&Shiffman.png|thumb|alt=Simple bar chart says "Varenicline + support" about 16, "NRT/bupropion + support" about 12.5, "NRT alone" about 7, "Telephone support" about 6, "Group support" about 5, "One-to-one support" about 4 and "Tailored online support" about 2.5.|Percent increase of success for six months over unaided attempts for each type of quitting (chart from West & Shiffman based on Cochrane review data<ref name=WestShiffman2007/>{{rp|59}}]]
Smokers who are hospitalised may be particularly motivated to quit.<ref name=USDHHS2008/>{{rp|149–150}} A 2007 Cochrane review found that interventions beginning during a hospital stay and continuing for one month or more after discharge were effective in producing abstinence.<ref>{{Cite journal | author = Rigotti NA, Munafo MR, Stead LF | editor1-last = Rigotti | editor1-first = Nancy | title = Interventions for smoking cessation in hospitalised patients | journal = Cochrane Database Syst Rev | issue = 3 | pages = CD001837 | year = 2007 | doi = 10.1002/14651858.CD001837.pub2 | pmid = 17636688 | url = http://www2.cochrane.org/reviews/en/ab001837.html}}</ref>

==Comparison of success rates==
Comparison of success rates across interventions can be difficult because of different definitions of "success" across studies.<ref name=ACS-success/>  Robert West and Saul Shiffman, authorities in this field recognised by Government Health Departments in a number of countries <ref name=WestShiffman2007/>{{rp|73,76,80}}, have concluded that, used together, "behavioural support" and "medication" can quadruple the chances that a quit attempt will be successful.
In 2010 the US [[National Tobacco Cessation Collaborative]] (NTCC) created "What Works to Quit: A Guide to Quit Smoking Methods" which compares the efficacy and cost of 17 smoking cessation methods.<ref name=NTCCQuit>{{cite web|title=What Works To Quit|url=http://whatworkstoquit.tobacco-cessation.org/NTCCguide.pdf|publisher=The National Tobacco Cessation Collaborative|accessdate=2011-02-27}}</ref>  The guide, based on the 2008 Guideline, reports that smokers using a combination method of pharmacological and psychosocial approaches have the most success compared to those who use pharmaceutical or psychosocial approaches in isolation.<ref name=NTCCQuit/>

A 2008 systematic review in the ''[[European Journal of Cancer Prevention]]'' found that group behavioural therapy was the most effective intervention strategy for smoking cessation, followed by [[bupropion]], intensive physician advice, nicotine replacement therapy, individual counselling, telephone counselling, nursing interventions, and tailored self-help interventions; the study did not discuss [[varenicline]].<ref name=Lemmens2008/>
[[File:Smoking insula.jpg|thumb|Individuals who sustained damage to the insula were able to more easily abstain from smoking.<ref>{{Cite journal | author = Naqvi NH, Rudrauf D, Damasio H, Bechara A | title = Damage to the insula disrupts addiction to cigarette smoking | journal = Science | volume = 315 | issue = 5811 | pages = 531–4 | year = 2007 | doi = 10.1126/science.1135926 | pmid = 17255515 }}</ref>]]

==Factors affecting success==
Quitting can be harder for individuals with dark pigmented skin compared to individuals with pale skin since nicotine has an affinity for [[melanin]]-containing tissues. Studies suggest this can cause the phenomenon of increased [[Nicotine#Dependence|nicotine dependence]] and lower smoking cessation rate in darker pigmented individuals.<ref>{{Cite journal | author=King G, Yerger VB, Whembolua GL, Bendel RB, Kittles R, Moolchan ET | title = Link between facultative melanin and tobacco use among African Americans | journal = Pharmacol Biochem Behav | volume = 92 | issue=4 | pages = 589–96 | year = 2009 | doi = 10.1016/j.pbb.2009.02.011 | pmid = 19268687 | url = http://chicago.medicine.uic.edu/UserFiles/Servers/Server_442934/File/IHG/Kittleslab/documents/Melanin%20and%20Nicotine%20Article%20-%20Publication.pdf }}</ref>

There is an important social component to smoking. A 2008 study of a densely interconnected network of over 12,000 individuals found that smoking cessation by any given individual reduced the chances of others around them lighting up by the following amounts: a spouse by 67%, a sibling by 25%, a friend by 36%, and a coworker by 34%.<ref>{{cite journal| author=Christakis NA, Fowler JH| title=The collective dynamics of smoking in a large social network| journal=N Engl J Med| volume=358| issue=21| pages=2249–58| year=2008| pmid=18499567| pmc=2822344| doi=10.1056/NEJMsa0706154| url = http://www.nejm.org/doi/full/10.1056/NEJMsa0706154}}</ref><!--For preceding ref, pmc deleted because PubMed Central version is author manuscript, not final.--> Nevertheless, a [[Cochrane Collaboration|Cochrane]] review determined that interventions to increase social support for a smoker's cessation attempt did not increase long-term quit rates.<ref>{{Cite journal | author = Park EW, Schultz JK, Tudiver F, Campbell T, Becker L | editor1-last = Park | editor1-first = Eal Whan | title = Enhancing partner support to improve smoking cessation | journal = Cochrane Database Syst Rev | issue = 3 | pages = CD002928 | year = 2004 | doi = 10.1002/14651858.CD002928.pub2 | pmid = 15266469 | url = http://www2.cochrane.org/reviews/en/ab002928.html}}</ref>

Smokers who are trying to quit are faced with social influences that may persuade them to conform and continue smoking. Cravings are easier to detain when ones environment does not provoke the habit. If a person who stopped smoking has close relationships with active smokers they are often put into situations that make the urge to conform more tempting. However, in a small group with at least one other not smoking, the likelihood of conformity decreases. 
The social influence to smoke cigarettes has been proven to rely on simple variables. One researched variable depends on whether the influence is from a friend or non-friend.  In [http://www.tandfonline.com/doi/full/10.1080/02732173.2012.646163 “Friendship and Conformity in Group Opinions”]<ref>Social Influences  Friendship and Conformity  Retrieved from http://www.tandfonline.com/doi/full/10.1080/02732173.2012.646163</ref> the research shows that individuals are 77% more likely to conform to non-friends, while close friendships decrease conformity.  Therefore, if an acquaintance offers a cigarette as a polite gesture, the person who has stopped smoking will be more likely to break his commitment than if a friend had offered.  


Smokers with [[major depressive disorder]] may be less successful at quitting smoking than non-depressed smokers.<ref name=USDHHS2008/>{{rp|81}}<ref name=Glassman1990>{{Cite journal | doi = 10.1001/jama.1990.03450120058029 | author = Glassman AH, Helzer JE, Covey LS, Cottler LB, Stetner F, Tipp JE, Johnson J | title = Smoking, smoking cessation, and major depression | journal = JAMA | volume = 264 | issue = 12 | pages = 1546–9 | year = 1990 | url = http://jama.ama-assn.org/content/264/12/1546.full.pdf | pmid = 2395194 }}</ref>

Relapse (resuming smoking after quitting) has been related to psychological issues such as low [[self-efficacy]]<ref>{{Cite journal | author = Condiotte MM, Lichtenstein E | title = Self-efficacy and relapse in smoking cessation programs | journal = J Consult Clin Psychol | volume = 49 | issue = 5 | pages = 648–58 | year = 1981 | doi = 10.1037/0022-006X.49.5.648 | pmid = 7287974 }}</ref> or non-optimal coping responses;<ref>{{Cite journal | author = Shiffman S | title = Relapse following smoking cessation: a situational analysis | journal = J Consult Clin Psychol | volume = 50 | issue = 1 | pages = 71–86 | year = 1982 | doi = 10.1037/0022-006X.50.1.71 | pmid = 7056922 }}</ref> however, psychological approaches to prevent relapse have not been proven to be successful.<ref name=Hajek2009>{{Cite journal | author = Hajek P, Stead LF, West R, Jarvis M, Lancaster T | editor1-last = Stead | editor1-first = Lindsay F | title = Relapse prevention interventions for smoking cessation | journal = Cochrane Database Syst Rev | issue = 1 | pages = CD003999 | year = 2009 | doi = 10.1002/14651858.CD003999.pub3 | pmid = 19160228 | url = http://www2.cochrane.org/reviews/en/ab003999.html}}</ref>  In contrast, varenicline may help some relapsed smokers.<ref name=Hajek2009/>

