===Symptoms===
In a 2007 review of the effects of abstinence from tobacco, Hughes concluded that "anger, anxiety, depression, difficulty concentrating, impatience, insomnia, and restlessness are valid withdrawal symptoms that peak within the first week and last 2–4 weeks."<ref name=Hughes2007>{{Cite journal  | author = Hughes JR | title = Effects of abstinence from tobacco: valid symptoms and time course | journal = Nicotine Tob Res | volume = 9  | issue = 3  | pages = 315–27 |  year = 2007 | doi = 10.1080/14622200701188919 | pmid = 17365764 | url=http://ntr.oxfordjournals.org/content/9/3/315.full.pdf }}</ref> In contrast, "constipation, cough, dizziness, increased dreaming, and mouth ulcers" may or may not be symptoms of withdrawal, while drowsiness, fatigue, and certain physical symptoms ("dry mouth, flu symptoms, headaches, heart racing, skin rash, sweating, tremor") were not symptoms of withdrawal.<ref name=Hughes2007/>

===Weight gain===
Giving up smoking is associated with an average weight gain of {{convert|4|-|5|kg|lb}} after 12 months, most of which occurs within the first three months of quitting.<ref>{{cite journal |author=H.-J. Aubin, A. Farley, D. Lycett, P. Lahmek, P. Aveyard. |title=Weight gain in smokers after quitting cigarettes: meta-analysis |journal=BMJ-British Medical Journal |issue=345|year=2012 |pmid= |doi=10.1136/bmj.e4439}}</ref>

The possible causes of the weight gain include:
* Smoking over-expresses the gene [[AZGP1]] which stimulates [[lipolysis]], so smoking cessation may decrease lipolysis.<ref name=Vanni2009>{{cite journal | title = Cigarette smoking induces overexpression of a fat-depleting gene AZGP1 in the human | journal=Chest | volume=135 | issue = 5 | pages=1197–208 | year=2009 | pmid=19188554 | url = http://chestjournal.chestpubs.org/content/135/5/1197.long| author=Vanni H, Kazeros A, Wang R, Harvey BG, Ferris B, De BP, Carolan BJ, Hübner RH, O'Connor TP, Crystal RG | doi = 10.1378/chest.08-1024 | pmc = 2679098 }}</ref>
* Smoking suppresses appetite, which may be caused by nicotine's effect on central [[Autonomic nervous system|autonomic]] neurons (e.g., via regulation of [[melanin concentrating hormone]] neurons in the [[hypothalamus]]).<ref name=Jo2002>{{Cite journal | author = Jo YH, Talmage DA, Role LW | title = Nicotinic receptor-mediated effects on appetite and food intake | journal = J Neurobiol | volume = 53 | issue = 4 | pages = 618–32 | year = 2002 | doi = 10.1002/neu.10147 | pmid = 12436425 | pmc = 2367209}}</ref>
* Heavy smokers are reported to burn 200 calories per day more than non-smokers eating the same diet.<ref>{{cite book|title= Johns Hopkins family health book|author=Klag MJ|year=1999|page=86|publisher=HarperCollins| location = New York| isbn=0-06-270149-5}}</ref> Possible reasons for this phenomenon include nicotine's ability to increase energy metabolism or nicotine's effect on peripheral neurons.<ref name=Jo2002/>

The 2008 Guideline suggests that sustained-release bupropion, nicotine gum, and nicotine lozenge be used "to delay weight gain after quitting."<ref name=USDHHS2008/>{{rp|173–176}} However, a 2012 Cochrane review concluded that "The data are not sufficient to make strong clinical recommendations for effective programmes" for preventing weight gain.<ref>{{cite journal |author=Farley AC, Hajek P, Lycett D, Aveyard P |title=Interventions for preventing weight gain after smoking cessation |journal=Cochrane Database Syst Rev |issue=1 |pages=CD006219 |year=2012 |pmid=22258966 |doi=10.1002/14651858.CD006219.pub3 |volume=1}}</ref>

===Depression===
Like other physically addictive drugs, nicotine withdrawal causes down-regulation of the production of dopamine and other stimulatory neurotransmitters as the brain attempts to compensate for artificial stimulation.  Therefore, when people stop smoking, depressive symptoms or actual depression may result.<ref name=Glassman1990/><ref>{{Cite journal | author = Covey LS, Glassman AH, Stetner F | title = Major depression following smoking cessation | journal = Am J Psychiatry | volume = 154 | issue = 2 | pages = 263–5 | year = 1997 | pmid = 9016279 | url = http://ajp.psychiatryonline.org/cgi/reprint/154/2/263}}</ref> This side effect of smoking cessation may be particularly common in women, as depression is more common among women than among men.<ref name=Borrelli1996>{{Cite journal | author = Borrelli B, Bock B, King T, Pinto B, Marcus BH| title = The impact of depression on smoking cessation in women | journal = Am J Prev Med | volume = 12 | issue = 5 | pages = 378–87 | year =1996 | pmid = 8909649 }}</ref>

===Anxiety===
A recent study by [[The British Journal of Psychiatry]] has found that smokers who successfully quit feel less anxious afterwards with the effect being greater among those who had mood and anxiety disorders than those that smoked for pleasure.<ref name=bjp>{{cite journal | author = Máirtín S. McDermott, Theresa M. Marteau, Gareth J. Hollands, Matthew Hankins and Paul Aveyard | title = Change in anxiety following successful and unsuccessful attempts at smoking cessation: cohort study | journal = BJP | url = http://bjp.rcpsych.org/content/202/1/62 }}</ref>

==Health benefits==
Many of tobacco's detrimental health effects can be reduced or largely removed through smoking cessation. The health benefits over time of stopping smoking include:<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.cancer.org/healthy/stayawayfromtobacco/guidetoquittingsmoking/guide-to-quitting-smoking-benefits|title=When smokers quit -- What are the benefits over time? |author=American Cancer Society |date=2011-01-31 |accessdate=2011-02-20}}</ref>
* Within 20 minutes after quitting, [[blood pressure]] and [[heart rate]] decrease
* Within 12 hours, [[carbon monoxide]] levels in the blood decrease to normal
* Within 48 hours, nerve endings and sense of smell and taste both start recovering
* Within 3 months, [[Circulatory system|circulation]] and [[Spirometry|lung function]] improve
* Within 9 months, there are decreases in cough and shortness of breath
* Within 1 year, the risk of [[coronary disease|coronary heart disease]] is cut in half
* Within 5 years, the risk of [[stroke]] falls to the same as a non-smoker, and the risks of many cancers (mouth, throat, esophagus, bladder, cervix) decrease significantly
* Within 10 years, the risk of dying from [[lung cancer]] is cut in half,<ref>{{Cite journal | author = Peto R, Darby S, Deo H, Silcocks P, Whitley E, Doll R | title = Smoking, smoking cessation, and lung cancer in the UK since 1950: combination of national statistics with two case-control studies | journal = BMJ | volume = 321 | issue = 7257 | pages = 323–9 | year = 2000 | doi = 10.1136/bmj.321.7257.323 | pmc = 27446 | pmid = 10926586 |url = http://www.bmj.com/content/321/7257/323.full |accessdate=2011-02-15}}</ref> and the risks of larynx and pancreas cancers decrease
* Within 15 years, the risk of coronary heart disease drops to the level of a non-smoker; lowered risk for developing COPD (chronic obstructive pulmonary disease)

The [[British doctors study]] showed that those who stopped smoking before they reached 30 years of age lived almost as long as those who never smoked.<ref name="Doll 2004">{{cite journal |author=Doll R, Peto R, Boreham J, Sutherland I |title=Mortality in relation to smoking: 50 years' observations on male British doctors |journal=BMJ |volume=328 |issue=7455 |page=1519 |year=2004 |pmid=15213107 |pmc=437139 |doi=10.1136/bmj.38142.554479.AE |url=http://www.bmj.com/content/328/7455/1519.long }}</ref> Stopping in one's sixties can still add three years of healthy life.<ref name="Doll 2004"/>  A randomized trial from the U.S. and Canada showed that a smoking cessation program lasting 10 weeks decreased mortality from all causes over 14 years later.<ref>{{Cite journal | author = Anthonisen NR, Skeans MA, Wise RA, Manfreda J, Kanner RE, Connett JE; Lung Health Study Research Group | title = The effects of a smoking cessation intervention on 14.5-year mortality: a randomized clinical trial | journal = Ann Intern Med | volume = 142 | issue = 4 | pages = 233–9 | year = 2005 | url = http://www.annals.org/content/142/4/233.full | pmid = 15710956 }}</ref>

Another published study, "Smoking Cessation Reduces Postoperative Complications: A Systematic Review and Meta-analysis," examined six randomized trials and 15 observational studies to look at the effects of preoperative smoking cessation on postoperative complications. The findings were: 1) taken together, the studies demonstrated decreased likelihood of postoperative complications in patients who ceased smoking prior to surgery; 2) overall, each week of cessation prior to surgery increased the magnitude of the effect by 19%. A significant positive effect was noted in trials where smoking cessation occurred at least four weeks prior to surgery; 3) For the six randomized trials, they demonstrated on average a relative risk reduction of 41% for postoperative complications.<ref>{{cite web|url = http://journalistsresource.org/studies/society/health/smoking-cessation-postoperative |title = Smoking Cessation Reduces Postoperative Complications |publisher = Journalist's Resource.org }}</ref>

Nicotine dependence is the most common form of chemical dependence in the United States and is as addictive as heroin or cocaine. Even a small dose of nicotine (that found in a cigarette) can cause significant changes in the functioning of numerous organs and systems in the body. Cigarette smoke contains 7,000 chemicals, hundreds of which are toxic and 70 of which are known to cause cancer. Smoking cessation is imperative if one wants to become free from nicotine dependence.{{Citation needed|date=April 2013}}

== Cost-effectiveness ==
[[Image:Smokers-as-a-percentage-of-adult-pop.jpg|thumb|500px|Smokers as a percentage of the population for the United States, the Netherlands, Norway, Japan, and Finland.]]
[[Cost-effectiveness analysis|Cost-effectiveness analyses]] of smoking cessation activities have shown that they increase [[quality-adjusted life year]]s (QALYs) at costs comparable with other types of interventions to treat and prevent disease.<ref name=USDHHS2008/>{{rp|134–137}}  Studies of the cost-effectiveness of smoking cessation include:
* In a 1997 U.S. analysis, the estimated cost per QALY varied by the type of cessation approach, ranging from group intensive counselling without nicotine replacement at $1108 per QALY to minimal counselling with nicotine gum at $4542 per QALY.<ref>{{Cite journal | doi = 10.1001/jama.278.21.1759 | author = Cromwell J, Bartosch WJ, Fiore MC, Hasselblad V, Baker T | title = Cost-effectiveness of the clinical practice recommendations in the AHCPR guideline for smoking cessation | journal = JAMA | volume = 278 | issue = 21 | pages = 1759–66 | year = 1997 | pmid = 9388153 | url = http://jama.ama-assn.org/content/278/21/1759.full.pdf}}</ref>
* A study from [[Erasmus University Rotterdam]] limited to people with [[chronic obstructive pulmonary disease]] found that the cost-effectiveness of minimal counselling, intensive counselling, and drug therapy were €16,900, €8,200, and €2,400 per QALY gained respectively.<ref>{{Cite journal | author = Hoogendoorn M, Feenstra TL, Hoogenveen RT, Rutten-van Mölken MP | title = Long-term effectiveness and cost-effectiveness of smoking cessation interventions in patients with COPD | journal = Thorax | volume = 65 | issue = 8 | pages = 711–8 |year = 2010 | doi = 10.1136/thx.2009.131631 | pmid = 20685746 }}</ref>
* Among [[National Health Service]] smoking cessation clients in [[Glasgow]], pharmacy one-to-one counselling cost £2,600 per QALY gained and group support cost £4,800 per QALY gained.<ref>{{Cite journal | author = Bauld L, Boyd KA, Briggs AH, Chesterman J, Ferguson J, Judge K, Hiscock R | title = One-year outcomes and a cost-effectiveness analysis for smokers accessing group-based and pharmacy-led cessation services | journal = Nicotine Tob Res | volume = 13 | issue = 2 | pages = 135–45 | year = 2011 | doi = 10.1093/ntr/ntq222 | pmid = 21196451 }}</ref>

==Statistical trends==
The frequency of smoking cessation among smokers varies across countries.  Smoking cessation increased in Spain between 1965 and 2000,<ref>{{Cite journal | author = Schiaffino A, Fernández E, Kunst A, Borrell C, García M, Borràs JM, Mackenbach JP | title = Time trends and educational differences in the incidence of quitting smoking in Spain (1965–2000) | journal = Prev Med | volume = 45 | issue = 2–3 | pages = 226–32 | year = 2007 | doi = 10.1016/j.ypmed.2007.05.009 | pmid = 17604832}}</ref> in Scotland between 1998 and 2007,<ref>{{Cite journal | author = Fowkes FJ, Stewart MC, Fowkes FG, Amos A, Price JF | title = Scottish smoke-free legislation and trends in smoking cessation | journal = Addiction | volume = 103 | issue = 11 | pages = 1888–95 | year = 2008 | doi = 10.1111/j.1360-0443.2008.02350.x | pmid = 19032538 }}</ref> and in Italy after 2000.<ref>{{Cite journal | author = Federico B, Costa G, Ricciardi W, Kunst AE | title = Educational inequalities in smoking cessation trends in Italy, 1982–2002 | journal = Tob Control | volume = 18 | issue = 5 | pages = 393–8 | year = 2009 | doi = 10.1136/tc.2008.029280 | pmid = 19617220 }}</ref> In contrast, in the U.S. the cessation rate was "stable (or varied little)" between 1998 and 2008,<ref>{{Cite journal | author1 = Zuo, Xiaoan | author2 = Zhao, Halin | author3 = Zhao, Xueyong | author4 = Guo, Yirui | author5 = Yun, Jianying | author6 = Wang, Shaokun | author7 = Miyasaka, Takafumi | title = Cigarette smoking among adults and trends in smoking cessation - United States, 2008 | journal = MMWR Morb Mortal Wkly Rep | volume = 58 | issue = 44 | pages = 1227–32 | year = 2009 | doi =  | pmid = 19910909 | url = http://www.cdc.gov/mmwr/preview/mmwrhtml/mm5844a2.htm | bibcode = }}</ref> and in China smoking cessation rates declined between 1998 and 2003.<ref>{{Cite journal | author = Qian J, Cai M, Gao J, Tang S, Xu L, Critchley JA | title = Trends in smoking and quitting in China from 1993 to 2003: National Health Service Survey data | journal = Bull World Health Organ | volume = 88 | issue = 10 | pages = 769–76 | year = 2010 | doi = 10.2471/BLT.09.064709 | pmid = 20931062 | pmc = 2947036}}</ref>

Nevertheless, in a growing number of countries there are now more ex-smokers than smokers.<ref name=Chapman-MacKenzie/> For example, in the U.S. as of 2010, there were 47 million ex-smokers and 46 million smokers.<ref>{{cite news|author=Martin, Anya|title=What it takes to quit smoking|date=May 13, 2010|url=http://www.marketwatch.com/story/what-it-takes-to-quit-smoking-2010-05-13?pagenumber=2|page=2|work=MarketWatch|publisher=Dow Jones|accessdate=May 14, 2010}}</ref>
